IF Females be wanting, Looking-Glasses may serve to make reflexion of themselves;
so these Creatures, deluded by their own pictures, are drawn thither. Also Liquors
may serve in stead of Glasses.



Jackdaws love themselves: the Fowler following to take them, invents such wayes;
for where he sees they flock, there he sets a Bason full of Oyl; the curious Bird
coming thither, sits on the brim of the Vessel, looking down to see her own Picture;
and because she thinks that she sees another Jackdaw, she hastens to flee down, and
so falls into the Oyl, and the thick Oyl sticks to her, and so she is catched without
snares or nets.

